WEBVTT

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:05.680
<v Teacher>So I want to talk about something now that's different in Spanish.

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:08.880
<v Teacher>And first I want to speak about what this means

00:00:09.139 --> 00:00:19.779
<v Teacher>Rather than an obstacle to learning, it's part of the experience of learning a new language which can make you realize that in your own language, you are both

00:00:20.199 --> 00:00:27.480
<v Teacher>Permitted and obliged to perceive and express the world in a certain way.

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:32.599
<v Teacher>There's two important kind of contradictory concepts here almost

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:35.500
<v Teacher>It permits you and obliges you.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:41.100
<v Teacher>It allows you and requires you to perceive and to express

00:00:41.420 --> 00:00:43.420
<v Teacher>the world in a certain way.

00:00:43.420 --> 00:00:48.460
<v Teacher>So in Spanish we have two verbs for to be.

00:00:48.460 --> 00:00:52.860
<v Teacher>So remember to be is is, am, are, we get all of this from to be.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:55.579
<v Teacher>We don't say I be, we say I am.

00:00:55.880 --> 00:01:00.360
<v Teacher>So we have <b>ser</b>. This is where <b>es</b> comes from.

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:02.680
<v Teacher>This is where <b>son</b> comes from.

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:12.840
<v Teacher>And <b>ser</b> is about characteristics. When we refer to the characteristics of something. Actually <b>un ser</b> is <i>a being</i>.

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:18.700
<v Teacher>We said that some form of the verb is often the noun; here it's the complete form.

00:01:18.700 --> 00:01:22.860
<v Teacher><b>Un ser</b> is <i>a being</i>. <b>Un ser humano</b> is what?

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:24.600
<v Student>A human being.

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:27.000
<v Teacher>A human being. And we could have found <b>humano</b>,

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.520
<v Teacher>even though there's no rule to find <b>humano</b>, that word. We have <i>humanity</i>.

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:35.640
<v Teacher>The words with <i>-ity</i> end how in Spanish?

00:01:36.079 --> 00:01:37.039
<v Student><b>Humanidad</b>.

00:01:37.039 --> 00:01:42.880
<v Teacher><b>Humanidad</b>. And then we can probably guess then that <i>human</i> is <b>humano</b>. <b>Un ser humano</b> is <i>a human being</i>.

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:58.560
<v Teacher>So <b>ser</b> refers to things that are characteristic of something. Then <b>estar</b>, which is the other <i>to be</i>, <b>estar</b> refers to states - states we are in. The word <i>state</i> is related to <b>estar</b>.

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:12.440
<v Teacher>So Spanish permits us, allows us, but also obliges us, when we are perceiving and expressing the world around us, to make a decision and to think about something.

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:16.100
<v Teacher>Is this a state, or is it a characteristic?

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:18.260
<v Teacher>So this kind of sounds very abstract right now.

00:02:18.260 --> 00:02:20.580
<v Teacher>So let's look at some examples.

00:02:20.420 --> 00:02:27.300
<v Teacher>To be tired, do you think this is a state or do you think it's a characteristic of you to be tired?

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:31.060
<v Teacher>Is it a state you're in, or is it a characteristic of you?

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:32.480
<v Student>It's a state.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:33.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:39.200
<v Teacher>Where you are, is it a state you are in or is it a characteristic of you where you are?

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:40.160
<v Student>A state.

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:40.960
<v Teacher>A state.

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:46.160
<v Teacher>To be a good or a bad person, you think this is a characteristic of you or a state?

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:47.840
<v Teacher>Characteristic.

00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:49.040
<v Student>Characteristic.

00:02:49.040 --> 00:03:00.620
<v Teacher>So it's very very important to kind of snub out now any temptation that you might have to simplify this to <i>temporary</i> and <i>permanent</i>.

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:13.200
<v Teacher>This is what most learners do, and actually what many teachers do: simplify this concept to <i>temporary</i> and <i>permanent</i>. Which, if you think about it this way, will work most of the time, but not all of the time.

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:17.320
<v Teacher>We want to think in this way: is it a state or is it a characteristic?

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:23.080
<v Teacher>For example, if I say <i>I am a student</i>, it's not very permanent is it?

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:29.840
<v Teacher>But is it a state or a characteristic? My profession or my occupation.

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:32.079
<v Student>It should be a state you're in.

00:03:32.079 --> 00:03:35.280
<v Teacher>It's temporary, but that doesn't make it a state.

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:41.700
<v Teacher>Your profession, according to Spanish, is characteristic of you. Even if you do it for five minutes.

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:45.860
<v Student>I guess it's the same, for example, as you said before with the word <i>aggressive</i>.

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:51.480
<v Student>Someone can be aggressive and they can change, so that stops it from being permanent.

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:54.760
<v Student>But it's still a characteristic.

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:55.100
<v Teacher>Exactly.

00:03:55.100 --> 00:04:00.860
<v Teacher>And we will see actually some adjectives we can use with both <b>ser</b> and <b>estar</b> to give different meanings.

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:05.100
<v Teacher>But the great bulk of them go with one or the other.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:13.640
<v Teacher>This is Spanish conceptually deciding whether it's a characteristic or a state; forcing us to make this differentiation and to express it.

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:18.260
<v Teacher>Let's look at the forms. Let's look at the forms of <b>estar</b> to begin.

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:24.020
<v Teacher>Now <i>I am</i> from <b>estar</b> is <b>estoy</b>. <b>Estoy</b>.

00:04:24.020 --> 00:04:29.540
<v Teacher>So it ends <i>-oy</i>. We already saw another verb that ends <i>-oy</i>, which is <b>voy</b>:

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:32.979
<v Teacher><i>I go</i> or <i>I'm going</i>. <b>Estoy</b>.

00:04:32.979 --> 00:04:33.560
<v Student><b>Estoy</b>.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:38.680
<v Teacher><b>Estoy</b>. Now <i>to be</i> is a very irregular verb in most languages.

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:43.160
<v Teacher>Look at English: from <i>to be</i> we get <i>am</i>, <i>is</i>, <i>are</i>, <i>was</i>.

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:46.480
<v Teacher>But this is actually not so irregular.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:49.520
<v Teacher>We have this little irregularity <i>-oy</i>, <b>estoy</b>.

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:51.360
<v Student><b>Estoy</b>.

00:04:51.360 --> 00:05:03.479
<v Teacher>And the other irregularity that we have is that this verb is the only verb in the entire Spanish language that doesn't have the accent on the penultimate syllable in the present tense.

00:05:03.479 --> 00:05:06.660
<v Teacher>So it's not "<b>éstoy</b>", it's <b>estoy</b>; the accent is on the ending.

00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:11.300
<v Teacher>This hasn't happened until now, and it won't happen again.

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:13.940
<v Teacher>So we have <b>estar</b> and from <b>estar</b> we have <b>estoy</b>.

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:19.699
<v Teacher>Now all of the other forms are regular, we build them how we would expect to, with the exception

00:05:19.699 --> 00:05:28.140
<v Teacher>that the accent will be on the last syllable. And it's the only verb in the entire present tense that has this characteristic.

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:35.520
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>he is</i> / <i>she is</i> / <i>it is</i> / <i>you are</i>, from <b>estar</b>, using <b>estar</b>?

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:39.680
<v Student><b>Está</b>.

00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:42.639
<v Teacher><b>Está</b>. <i>They</i> or <i>for you guys</i>:

00:05:42.639 --> 00:05:43.600
<v Student><b>Están</b>.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:46.240
<v Teacher>Good. And make it for <i>you</i> (informal):

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:48.319
<v Student><b>Estás</b>.

00:05:48.319 --> 00:05:53.039
<v Teacher>Good. And for the "we" version, the accent is where it should be because we're adding two syllables.

00:05:53.039 --> 00:05:54.400
<v Teacher>So give me the "we" version.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:55.039
<v Student><b>Estamos</b>.

00:05:55.039 --> 00:05:57.120
<v Teacher><b>Estamos</b>. So that's it, that's your set.

00:05:57.120 --> 00:06:01.440
<v Teacher><b>Estoy</b>, <b>está</b>, <b>están</b>, <b>estás</b>, <b>estamos</b>.

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:07.980
<v Teacher>The word for <i>tired</i> is <b>cansado</b>, <b>cansado</b>.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:11.500
<v Student><b>Cansado</b>.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:12.700
<v Teacher><i>C-a-n-s-a-d-o</i>. <b>Cansado</b>.

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:13.340
<v Student><b>Cansado</b>.

00:06:13.340 --> 00:06:15.800
<v Teacher>Good. So how would you say <i>I am tired</i>? This is a state.

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:20.759
<v Student><b>Estoy cansada</b>.

00:06:20.759 --> 00:06:21.960
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:21.960 --> 00:06:23.479
<v Student><b>Estoy cansada</b>.

00:06:23.479 --> 00:06:24.040
<v Teacher><b>Estoy cansada</b>. Good.

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:29.320
<v Teacher><i>We are tired</i>, talking about a mixed or a masculine group?

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:31.000
<v Student><b>Estamos cansados</b>.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:32.759
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Estamos cansados</b>.

00:06:32.759 --> 00:06:35.320
<v Teacher>What if you are an all female group?

00:06:36.659 --> 00:06:39.139
<v Student><b>Estamos cansadas</b>.

00:06:39.139 --> 00:06:45.160
<v Teacher>Good. Now the word for <i>always</i> we said was <b>siempre</b>. <b>Siempre</b>.

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:56.199
<v Teacher>Now if you say <i>I'm always tired</i>, because <i>tired</i> as an adjective, as an idea, is a state, not a characteristic,

00:06:56.199 --> 00:07:03.300
<v Teacher>because we are looking at that - whether it's a state or a characteristic, rather than is it permanent or is it temporary - we're using <b>estar</b>.

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:09.100
<v Teacher>So even if you say <i>I'm always tired</i> it doesn't matter, you still use <b>estar</b>.

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:14.060
<v Teacher>So <b>siempre</b> is very flexible in this sentence. You can put it anywhere.

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:17.820
<v Teacher>The emphasis is going to change when you move it, but it's legal anywhere.

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:20.860
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I'm always tired</i>?

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:25.000
<v Student><b>Estoy cansada siempre</b>.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:31.900
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Estoy cansada siempre</b>. <b>Estoy siempre cansada</b>. <b>Siempre estoy cansada</b>. Or I would say <b>cansado</b>. Good.

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:40.200
<v Teacher>So we want to resist the temptation to simplify this concept to "temporary" and "permanent".

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:44.600
<v Teacher>We want to ask ourself "is it a state, or is it a characteristic?"

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:47.800
<v Teacher><i>To be tired</i>: is it a state or is it a characteristic?

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:57.160
<v Teacher>If we simplify it to <i>temporary</i> and <i>permanent</i>, most of the time it's going to work, this simplification.

00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:01.080
<v Teacher>But many times we're going to feel frustrated, feeling like there's something we don't understand because Spanish disagrees with us.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:12.940
<v Teacher>If we have the concepts of <i>characteristic</i> and <i>state</i>, the few times Spanish disagrees with what we consider a characteristic and state it's going to be an interesting point of perspective.

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:19.180
<v Teacher>For example, <b>muerto</b>. Which means:

00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:19.660
<v Student>Dead.

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:25.020
<v Teacher>Dead. Good. We looked at this briefly before as a part of <i>mortgage</i>, meaning <i>death-pact</i>.

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:29.440
<v Teacher><b>Muerto</b>, in Spanish, is a state. Death is a state.

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:34.880
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>I'm dead</i>, you would use <b>estar</b>. So how would you say that?

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:36.620
<v Student><b>Estoy muerta</b>.

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:40.300
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Estoy muerta</b>. And I would say <b>estoy muerto</b>.

00:08:40.300 --> 00:08:45.980
<v Teacher>And you can use it to say <i>I'm very tired</i> as well. <b>Estoy muerta</b>, <b>estoy muerto</b>. <i>I'm very tired</i>.

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:46.940
<v Teacher>Good.

